  Validation done: deploy/create-local-tls.sh passes bash -n. I did not execute the script because mkcert -install modifies your local trust store and the script applies a Kubernetes TLS secret.






• On your machine, the first thing to validate is this:

  kubectl -n sandboxes get secret sndbx-example-com-tls

  In my cluster that secret was missing, even though ingress referenced it. If it is missing on your other machine too, nginx serves its default/self-signed cert, and E2B keeps failing with the
  exact same SSL error.

  Run this from repo root:

  bash deploy/create-local-tls.sh
  kubectl apply -f deploy/runtime-gateway.yaml

  Then validate the pieces:

  kubectl -n sandboxes get secret sndbx-example-com-tls
  kubectl -n sandboxes get ingress sandbox-ingress -o yaml | grep -A6 tls

  Check the actual cert served by ingress:

  INGRESS_IP=$(minikube ip)

  openssl s_client \
    -connect "${INGRESS_IP}:443" \
    -servername "49983-test.sndbx.example.com" \
    -showcerts </dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -noout -subject -issuer -ext subjectAltName

  You should see SANs containing:

  DNS:api.sndbx.example.com
  DNS:*.sndbx.example.com

  Then validate Python/httpx trust specifically:

  SSL_CERT_FILE="$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" python - <<'PY'
  import httpx
  print(httpx.get("https://api.sndbx.example.com/health", timeout=10).status_code)
  PY

  If that works, run smoke the same way:

  SSL_CERT_FILE="$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" \
  API_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8001 \
  API_KEY=... \
  ./e2b_control_plane_smoke.py

  Important: mkcert -install trusting the cert in the OS is not always enough for Python, because httpx may use certifi. That is why SSL_CERT_FILE="$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" is the decisive
  validation.


  If https://api.sndbx.example.com/health still fails with SSL_CERT_FILE, then the smoke test is irrelevant for now. The cert being served is not trusted by that CA, or you are not hitting the
  ingress you think you are.

  Run these exact checks on that machine.

  1. Confirm Python sees the CA

  echo "$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem"
  test -f "$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" && echo OK

  SSL_CERT_FILE="$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" python - <<'PY'
  import os, ssl
  print("SSL_CERT_FILE =", os.environ.get("SSL_CERT_FILE"))
  print("default verify paths =", ssl.get_default_verify_paths())
  PY

  2. Check what cert ingress is actually serving

  openssl s_client \
    -connect api.sndbx.example.com:443 \
    -servername api.sndbx.example.com \
    -showcerts </dev/null 2>/dev/null \
    | openssl x509 -noout -subject -issuer -ext subjectAltName

  If issuer says something like Kubernetes Ingress Controller Fake Certificate, then your TLS secret is missing/wrong/not loaded by ingress.

  3. Verify with openssl using mkcert CA

  openssl s_client \
    -CAfile "$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" \
    -verify_return_error \
    -connect api.sndbx.example.com:443 \
    -servername api.sndbx.example.com </dev/null

  This must say:

  Verify return code: 0 (ok)

  If this does not pass, Python will not pass either.

  4. Check Kubernetes secret and ingress match

  kubectl -n sandboxes get secret sndbx-example-com-tls

  kubectl -n sandboxes get ingress sandbox-ingress -o jsonpath='{.spec.tls[*].secretName}{"\n"}'
  kubectl -n sandboxes get ingress sandbox-ingress -o jsonpath='{.spec.tls[*].hosts}{"\n"}'

  Expected for local raw deploy:

  sndbx-example-com-tls
  api.sndbx.example.com *.sndbx.example.com

  If you deployed through Helm with another namespace/domain, the secret name may be different, for example sndbx-sprinklr-com-tls. Then run:

  NAMESPACE=<your-namespace> \
  SANDBOX_DOMAIN=<your-domain> \
  TLS_SECRET_NAME=<secret-name-from-ingress> \
  bash deploy/create-local-tls.sh

  Example:

  NAMESPACE=sandboxes \
  SANDBOX_DOMAIN=sndbx.example.com \
  TLS_SECRET_NAME=sndbx-example-com-tls \
  bash deploy/create-local-tls.sh

  5. Force curl/Python through the exact CA

  curl --cacert "$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" https://api.sndbx.example.com/health

  Then:

  SSL_CERT_FILE="$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem" python - <<'PY'
  import httpx
  print(httpx.get("https://api.sndbx.example.com/health", timeout=10).text)
  PY

  Do not run the E2B smoke until these pass. If they fail, paste outputs from steps 2, 3, and 4. That will tell us exactly whether it is wrong cert, wrong ingress, wrong namespace, wrong secret
  name, or DNS pointing somewhere else.
